			<div class="content" id="post-content-3702321">
									

<p>I'm a little iffy on these for a few reasons. One critique I have is that almost all of your categories only have one example. I'm not really seeing how the mix of physics and fictional/outdated science terms provides a real common structural underpinning to these (akin to Humes or the time travel guide), so they still kinda feel like one-offs that get their own labels. (Also it's possible I just didn't get the science connections; my physics is quite rusty.)</p>
<p>I do think the idea of sorting then by utility factors/characteristics is neat, though.</p>
<p>I'm also used to the nature of Foundation multidimensional travel terminology being tied to the implied structure of the multiverse, such as the <a href="/multi-u-101">Hub-Branch-Floater</a> nomenclature used by Foundation <a href="/life-in-the-multiverse">explorers</a>, as well a similar description of Ways using <a href="/preliminary-report">empirical thaumaturgy</a> (this article is very compatible with your Broken Entry wormhole). (If you canon any of that.)</p>
<p>I'd be curious how the Foundation classifies tharmaturgical Ways versus &quot;naturally occurring&quot; anomalous wormholes versus, say, the MUTA-NT, which is based on understood tech but relies on Nexus weirdness. I tend to think the Foundation doesn't 100% trust any portal they didn't build, but they did use the kiddie pool to build a moon base&#8230;</p>

							</div>

								
					
